for classes (which is super rare, but understandable cause of your schedule and everything) as a prof, you were really encouraging with your words, and how you make adjustments for everyone. i appreciate all the extended time for submissions and for the neat and clear instructions and announcements every time. i like also when you keep being nice to us in a way you make us feel that we're more than just a student, that we also need to enjoy life and be safe always. and i thank you for that but as a student in like the real school learning scenario, i am not really learning that well specially that you were obviously expecting us to know stuff from the previous courses we took (which is sad also cause i am not learning that much too). the modules were helpful but im kind of dyslexic and i struggle with reading so much letters in one page hence me struggling with most stuff since its more on reading. your exams also are like out of the blue HAHAHAHA. i mean its hard when for both class, AI was a big help. but i think it kind of set us all off because we're not actually learning each and everything. more like we just learning the general part of coding. so i cant really say that i am good with it cause im not. i cant really rate you for how you teach us, cause were really not doing the usual classes, but i had fun with your subject and the days we had class. specially the random days where we do coding for nothing but just learning (database cmd). its fun and i get to understand everything.

However, I feel the learning experience could be better if more time was devoted to explaining complex topics in greater depth and not try to water it down by speeding through the process and missing a lot of important concepts along the way. This would help ensure that all key concepts are thoroughly covered, as the course content itself is already challenging and demands considerable effort on our part to grasp. Additionally, we would also appreciate timely announcements when unable to attend class, as it helps us stay productive with our time. Hopefully, future projects will have better-structured project guidelines, it would significantly contribute to a smoother learning experience.
